{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626372"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:36:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:36:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17072"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17072","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17072"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.19,0.35,0.15,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9762"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73517"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9762"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17072"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58986"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5267"},{"type":"tags","id":"5269"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22940"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23155"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73517"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EEchinocandins are antifungals utilised to manage severe fungal infections.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of echinocandins?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits DNA synthesis","Inhibits ergosterol synthesis","Inhibits beta-1,3-D-glucan synthase","Binds to ergosterol in cell membrane","Disrupts microtubule assembly"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EEchinocandins\u003Cstrong\u003E inhibit beta-1,3-D-glucan synthase\u003C/strong\u003E, an enzyme critical in fungal cell wall synthesis. This causes osmotic instability and subsequent cell death. This mechanism makes them effective against an array of Candida and Aspergillus species.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits DNA synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is not the mechanism of echinocandins, though some antimicrobials do work through DNA synthesis inhibition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits ergosterol synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action of azole antifungals, not echinocandins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBinds to ergosterol in cell membrane\u003C/strong\u003E describes how amphotericin B works, not echinocandins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisrupts microtubule assembly\u003C/strong\u003E is not a mechanism employed by any current antifungal medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEchinocandins are not effective against \u003Cem\u003ECryptococcus\u003C/em\u003E species as these fungi have less beta-glucan in their cell walls.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Echinocandins work by inhibiting beta-1,3-D-glucan synthase, disrupting fungal cell wall synthesis.","Echinocandins are effective against Candida species and Aspergillus species but not against Cryptococcus.","Examples of echinocandins include caspofungin, micafungin, and anidulafungin."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17072"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58986"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T22:23:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T22:24:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9762"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73517"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4936"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immune System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17